article.description:
Against the youngest team in the WNBA, the
Utah Starzz turned to Adrienne Goodson -- their oldest player -- for
a lift.
article.headline: Goodson comes on strong as Utah blitzes Detroit
article.linkText: Starzz look to oldest player for another big lift
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Against the youngest team in the WNBA, the Utah Starzz turned to Adrienne Goodson -- their oldest player -- for a lift. The 35-year-old Goodson scored 21 points and grabbed nine rebounds to lead the Starzz past the Detroit Shock 94-76 Monday night. ''Goody is the oldest one on the team, but she shouldn't even be thinking about retirement. She is our best scorer and has the most energy on the team,'' said Margo Dydek, who scored 12 points and had seven blocks and seven rebounds. Despite one of the league's most veteran squads, the Starzz improved to 2-0 in the second game of back-to-back sets. Los Angeles beat Utah 102-75 Sunday. ''I've being doing this a long time, but back-to-backs aren't really that bad. It's all about mental preparation, eating right and getting lots of fluids,'' said Goodson, who leads Utah in scoring with 16.4 points a game. Marie Ferdinand added 20 points as Utah (11-6) led for all but the first two minutes of the game. ''We came in focused. We wanted to put them out early and not give them any confidence. We jumped on them,'' Ferdinand said. Detroit rookie Swin Cash led all scorers with a season-high 25 points and Deanna Nolan had 18 points as Detroit (1-16) remained winless in 11 road games this year. ''We let the Starzz do whatever they wanted to in the first half. The effort wasn't there for whatever reason,'' Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. Sunday, Detroit acquired guard Elaine Powell and a 2003 first-round draft choice in exchange for veteran forward Wendy Palmer, the Shock's leading rebounder and second-leading scorer. Powell was not yet available to play Monday leaving the Shock short-handed. Detroit has lost three in a row after earning its first and only victory of the season. ''We're not a good basketball team, we know that,'' Laimbeer said. The Starzz feel just the opposite. ''We feel we can win whenever we play well, no matter who the opponent is. And we played well tonight,'' Goodson said. After trailing by as many as 22 points, the Shock pulled to 60-51 midway through the second half after a three-point play by Barbara Farris capped a 10-1 Detroit run. But the Starzz responded with an 11-4 surge, highlighted by a pair of Ferdinand's driving layups. Utah led 71-55 with 9:45 to play and the Shock couldn't get within 13 points the rest of the game. After the blowout defeat against the Sparks on Sunday, the Starzz breezed through their highest output of the season and the most points scored against the Shock by any team this year. ''We had good energy and we were aggressive all night. Not a bad comeback after a pretty good tail-kicking,'' Utah coach Candi Harvey said. The Starzz turned Detroit's 18 turnovers into 26 points and outscored the Shock in the paint 42-24. Even after missing their first five shots, the Starzz set a team record for points in a first half and led 51-32 at halftime. Notes
Utah improved to 6-1 against teams .500 or below. ... The Starzz are the tallest team in the WNBA averaging almost 6-foot-1, while Detroit has the youngest team (23.5 years). ... Detroit is 1-6 since Bill Laimbeer took over as head coach. ... Cleveland Cavaliers guard Andre Miller, who played at the University of Utah, was in attendance.
